name: Coupon
comment:
A coupon contains information about a percent-off discount you might want to apply to a customer.

Coupons only apply to invoices created for recurring subscriptions and invoice items; they do not apply to one-off charges.

duration.name: duration
duration.comment: One of forever, once, and repeating. Describes how long a customer who applies this coupon will get the discount.

amountOff.name: amountOff
amountOff.comment: Amount (in the currency specified) that will be taken off the subtotal of any invoices for this customer.

currency.name: currency
currency.comment: If amount_off has been set, the currency of the amount to take off.

durationInMonths.name: durationInMonths
durationInMonths.comment: If duration is repeating, the number of months the coupon applies. Null if coupon duration is forever or once.

maxRedemptions.name: maxRedemptions
maxRedemptions.comment: Maximum number of times this coupon can be redeemed, in total, before it is no longer valid.

metadata.name: metadata
metadata.comment: A set of key/value pairs that you can attach to a coupon object. It can be useful for storing additional information about the coupon in a structured format.

percentOff.name: percentOff
percentOff.comment: Percent that will be taken off the subtotal of any invoices for this customer for the duration of the coupon. For example, a coupon with percent_off of 50 will make a $100 invoice $50 instead.

redeemBy.name: redeemBy
redeemBy.comment: Date after which the coupon can no longer be redeemed

timesRedeemed.name: timesRedeemed
timesRedeemed.comment: Number of times this coupon has been applied to a customer.

valid.name: valid
valid.comment: Taking account of the above properties, whether this coupon can still be applied to a customer

retrieve.name: retrieve
retrieve.comment: Retrieves the coupon with the given ID.

delete.name: delete
delete.comment: You can delete coupons via the coupon management page of the Stripe dashboard. However, deleting a coupon does not affect any customers who have already applied the coupon; it means that new customers can't redeem the coupon. You can also delete coupons via the API.

hashCode.name: hashCode
hashCode.comment:
Get a hash code for this object.

All objects have hash codes. Hash codes are guaranteed to be the same for objects that are equal when compared using the equality operator ==. Other than that there are no guarantees about the hash codes. They will not be consistent between runs and there are no distribution guarantees.

If a subclass overrides stripe/stripe.Coupon.hashCode it should override the equality operator as well to maintain consistency.

runtimeType.name: runtimeType
runtimeType.comment: A representation of the runtime type of the object.

==.comment:
The equality operator.

The default behavior for all dart-core.Objects is to return true if and only if this and stripe/stripe.Coupon.==.other are the same object.

Override this method to specify a different equality relation on a class. The overriding method must still be an equivalence relation. That is, it must be:

  • Total: It must return a boolean for all arguments. It should never throw or return null.

  • Reflexive: For all objects o, o == o must be true.

  • Symmetric: For all objects o1 and o2, o1 == o2 and o2 == o1 must either both be true, or both be false.

  • Transitive: For all objects o1, o2, and o3, if o1 == o2 and o2 == o3 are true, then o1 == o3 must be true.

The method should also be consistent over time, so equality of two objects should not change over time, or at least only change if one of the objects was modified.

If a subclass overrides the equality operator it should override the stripe/stripe.Coupon.hashCode method as well to maintain consistency.

toString.name: toString
toString.comment: Returns a string representation of this object.

noSuchMethod.name: noSuchMethod
noSuchMethod.comment:
stripe/stripe.Coupon.noSuchMethod is invoked when users invoke a non-existent method on an object. The name of the method and the arguments of the invocation are passed to stripe/stripe.Coupon.noSuchMethod in an dart-core.Invocation. If stripe/stripe.Coupon.noSuchMethod returns a value, that value becomes the result of the original invocation.

The default behavior of stripe/stripe.Coupon.noSuchMethod is to throw a dart-core.NoSuchMethodError.
